 data sets A and B divided by the number of objects represented in data sets A and B, or StartFraction 1,875 plus 3,250 Over 125 EndFraction, which is equivalent to 41 meters. Therefore, the mean, in meters, of data set C is 41."}, {"id": "opensat-math-spr-554", "text": "A small business owner budgets dollar sign 2,200 to purchase candles. The owner must purchase a minimum of 200 candles to maintain the discounted pricing. If the owner pays dollar sign 4.90 per candle to purchase small candles and dollar sign 11.60 per candle to purchase large candles, what is the maximum number of large candles the owner can purchase to stay within the budget and maintain the discounted pricing?", "type": "grid_in", "topic": "math", "section": "math", "correct_answer": "182", "difficulty": "hard", "explanation": "The correct answer is 182. Let s represent the number of small candles the owner can purchase, and let script l represent the number of large candles the owner can purchase. It\u2019s given that the owner pays dollar sign 4.90 per candle to purchase small candles and dollar sign 11.60 per candle to purchase large candles. Therefore, the owner pays 4.90 s dollars for s small candles and 11.60 script l dollars for script l large candles, which means the owner pays a total of 4.90 s plus 11.60 script l dollars to purchase candles. It\u2019s given that the owner budgets dollar sign 2,200 to purchase candles. Therefore, 4.90 s plus 11.60 script l less than or equals 2,200. It\u2019s also given that the owner must purchase a minimum of 200 candles. Therefore, s plus script l greater than or equals 200. The inequalities 4.90 s plus 11.60 script l less than or equals 2,200 and s plus script l greater than or equals 200 can be combined into one compound inequality by rewriting the second inequality so that its left-hand side is equivalent to the left-hand side of the first inequality. Subtracting script l from both sides of the inequality s plus script l greater than or equals 200 